- S T E _ _ pattern: S is 1st, T is 4th, E is 5th.
- Letters NOT in the word: L, P.
- Letter A is in the word but NOT in position 2 or 3 (it got “-” both times it appeared in 3rd and 2nd positions respectively).

Therefore A must be in position 3.

We need a 5-letter English word of the form S _ A T E, with no L or P.

Possible letters for the second position (consonants not yet ruled out and not L or P):
B, C, D, F, G, H, J, K, M, N, Q, R, S, V, W, X, Y, Z

- SKATE (but K wasn’t tested)
- SHATE (archaic/obscure)

- S C A T E – see above
- S N A T E – not a word
- S R A T E – SRATE (not standard)
- S W A T E – SWATE (dialectal)

Among these, “SKATE” is the most recognizable standard English word, even though it places A in position 3 (which is allowed because the previous “-” for A only said “wrong position” – it never excluded position 3 explicitly). But let’s double-check:

In SLATE: A was in position 3 → “-” (so A is NOT in position 3)  
In SPATE: A was in position 2 → “-” (so A is NOT in position 2)
